{"key":"post-10971497","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10971497</id>\n<content>I've been saying for years that uncased bulk substrates fruit as well as cased.&amp;nbsp; A casing layer is just another step that takes time, allows for an additional vector of contamination, and returns little or no benefit.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;With proper attention to air exchange, lighting, and humidity, a casing layer is worthless.&amp;nbsp; In addition, having the light shine directly on the fully colonized substrate rather than through a casing layer stimulates a better pinset. Take a look in the grow logs forum of all the growers who are skipping the casing layer and getting equal or better results from fruiting uncased.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;About the only time a casing layer is required with cubensis is when you're trying to fruit straight grains.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10972122</next>\n<prev>10971493</prev>\n<first>10971306</first>\n<last>19901107</last>\n<when>1251730129</when>\n<utime>08/31/09 05:48 PM</utime>\n</post>"}